description_of_deviation: All the stored plasma, and urine samples that were collected during the Visit 20 clinic visit belonging to this participant were removed from their position in the freezer by a staff member not working on INDiGO and not replaced. As a result, they were left overnight at room temperature and allowed to thaw for a period of 19 hours and 35 mins (i.e. from 17:00 hrs on 28th May- 12:35 PM on 29th May 2023) afternoon on the 29th of May 2023). This is in contravention to Section 11.4 of version 4.0 of the INDiGO trial study protocol which requires aliquots of blood, breast milk and urine from participating women and blood and stool samples from infants to be kept frozen at - 70oC for future analysis.  In total: 2 aliquots of LH, 2 aliquots of EDTA and 4 aliquots of urine were affected.    The study PI is in discussion with the trial collaborators with regard to the likely impact this freeze-thaw-refreeze cycle will have on the samples and biomarker integrity. So far, the discussions have been reassuring from the point of view that the majority of the micronutrient biomarkers are likely to have been degraded in the samples.     We also note that this non-compliance report is being submitted beyond the recommended five-day window. This is because the full report from the laboratory with sample details was delayed in reaching the PI.
reason_for_deviation: Poor laboratory practice by a member of another project team.
steps_taken_to_correct_thi: The samples were immediately returned to the -80 freezer after notifying the lab manager about the incident.     Further, to prevent this from reoccurring, the following actions have been recommended by the INDiGO project team to the Keneba laboratory manager:    1. A study-specific freezer is allocated, so non-INDiGO staff are unable to access INDiGO samples.    2. Study freezers are only used for samples and not for the storage of dry ice, ice packs etc.

We propose a timeline of two hours from collection to delivery as the upper limit but will target 30 minutes as optimal.

description_of_deviation: This participant missed IP supplementation for more than 5 consecutive days (from 3rd June-19th June) in contravention of section 5.1.3 of version 5.0 of the INDiGO study protocol. Her weekly morbidity form was also not completed during this time.
reason_for_deviation: This participant travelled outside the study area to provide care for her sick mother. Although she notified the team before travelling, she could not be followed up at the coast for supplementation or form completion. However constant communication was maintained with her while she was away from the study area to address any safety concerns in the event she has any, and to know her return date for continuation of IP supplementation.
steps_taken_to_correct_thi: The investigation team is working on establishing a subunit of field staff that will be responsible for following up of participants who travelled outside the study area where and when possible. In addition, where a participant is absent from the study area and face to face follow up is not possible, her weekly morbidity forms will still be completed but using a phone interview, rather than face to face.

description_of_deviation: This participant's blood samples collected during her Week 20 Clinic visit were delivered to the lab beyond 30 mins from the time of collection as specified in the INDiGO trial SSP06_VenousBloodSampleCollection_v01_Final. However, they were delivered to the lab within 4 hours of collection as specified in the MRCG' unit SOP and no issues related to the samples' integrity was raised by the lab.
reason_for_deviation: This was an oversight from the team and the stipulated time for delivery of blood sample to the lab seems very short.
steps_taken_to_correct_thi: The attention of the team was call to this deviation. The SSP related to this process is revised and updated to align the time allowance for delivery of blood samples to the lab with its corresponding unit SOP.

description_of_deviation: All the stored plasma, and urine samples that were collected during the Visit 20 clinic visit belonging to this participant were removed from their position in the freezer by a staff member not working on INDiGO and not replaced. As a result, they were left overnight at room temperature and allowed to thaw for a period of 19 hours and 35 mins (i.e from 17:00 hrs on 28th May- 12:35 PM on 29th May 2023) afternoon on the 29th of May 2023). This is in contravention to Section 11.4 of version 4.0 of the INDiGO trial study protocol which requires aliquots of blood, breast milk and urine from participating women and blood and stool samples from infants to be kept frozen at - 70oC for future analysis.  In total: 2 aliquots of LH,  2 aliquots of EDTA  and 4 aliquots of urine were affected.    The study PI is in discussion with the trial collaborators with regards to the likely impact this freeze-thaw-refreeze cycle will have on the samples and biomarker integrity. So far, the discussions have been reassuring from the point of view that the majority of the micronutrient biomarkers are likely to have been degraded in the samples.     We also note that this non-compliance report is being submitted beyond the recommended five-day window. This is because the full report from the laboratory with sample details was delayed in reaching the PI.
reason_for_deviation: Poor laboratory practice by a member of another project team.
steps_taken_to_correct_thi: Sample were immediately returned to -80 freezer after notifying the lab manager about the incident.     Further, to prevent this from reoccurring, the following actions have been recommended by the INDiGO project team to the Keneba laboratory manager:  1.	A study specific freezer is allocated, so non-INDiGO staff are unable to access INDiGO samples.  2.	Study freezers are only used for samples and not for the storage of dry ice, ice packs etc.
